title: For Sale:  300 BLK Pistol
postcontent: One of a kind, piston operated, 300 BLK AR-15 pistol. What makes this unique is that it is a piston operated system, which is generally under-pressured for piston operated firearms. So why a piston system? You get much cleaner and cooler operation because no hot, carbon infused gas is being blown back into the receiver to cycle the action, making it a fantastic choice for the suppressor optimized 300 BLK cartridge. Suppressed rifles on a DI system are infamous for overpressure and excessive gas blowback, and a piston system will solve those worries. So far, I have run the pistol unsuppressed. 150 grain American Eagle works flawlessly and even locks back the action, and I have had moderate success with 120 grain Remington loads. I have yet to try this system with a suppressor, and it does not cycle reliable using subsonic loads and no suppressor, but I am sure you will be able to make it work with subsonic loads as long as you are using a barrel extension or a suppressor to give it the extra pressure it needs to cycle. If interested or if you have any questions, feel free to send me a text or an e-mail at REDACTED or REDACTED_________________________________________________Much research, and money, has been spent getting this build into working condition. Well over $1600 has been spent on this build, but I am selling it for only $900 because I am trying to cut my losses after getting this system to run. A complete list of parts can be found at the end of this post. Upper Receiver:-X-Products Side Charging Upper: $300-CMMG 8.0 in Barrel: $150-Adams Arms XLP Piston Kit: $300-Adams Arms Low Mass Bolt Carrier: $150-Mil-Spec bolt and firing pin: $100-VLTOR CASV Midlength free-float rail system: $250-Noveske KX3 Pig: $125-See All optic: $100Lower Receiver:-Black Rain Ordnance Billet Receiver: $150-Mil-Spec lower parts kit: $75-KAK Industries Blade kit: $100-Tubbs low power flatwire spring for 300 BLK: $30-Anti-Tilt buffer and carrier insert: $40As you can see from the parts listed, you will not be getting some project rifle that was thrown together in hopes that it would work. You will be getting a quality build that has been tested and rebuilt in order to ensure optimal performance, and you will not be disappointed.

title: For Sale:  WWII Flare Gun w/Flares
postcontent:
Selling a very nice English Flare gun with five (5) flares and tins.
The hammer and trigger are stamped "M601". There are three proof marks on the top of the chamber: A crown, a pair of crossed rifles, and a third one I cannot make out.
This flare gun is in excellent shape, fully functional and good cosmetics. There is a repaired chip on the butt of the grips.
The barrel has a small nubbin on the left hand side as if it wants a barrel extender or line attachment.
Here is what I learned about this model: It is a No. 2 Mk 5 model. The No1 Mk 5 is similar but has a longer flared barrel. The caliber is 1". The number M601 is a war time (WW2) British manufactures code.
M601 is made by the I.L. Berridge & Co of Leicester, England. They were commercial knitting machine manufactures, they are no longer in business. 
The flare tins have both been opened. One is full with three flares. One only has two flares. All appear in excellent condition, but I cannot vouch for their function.Asking $250 shipped.
